---------------------------------------------- --cleanUP DELETE FROM @output; ---------------------------------------------- --All youre looking for is Bytes Per Cluster. On my laptop, its 4096 bytes. Hey, I dont have dedicated SQL drives on here. --But what you want to see is Bytes Per Cluster : 65536. Again, thats 65536 bytes / 1024 = 64KB, --which is what you want for the disks that will hold SQL data and log files. DECLARE @svrName VARCHAR(255) DECLARE @sql VARCHAR(400) --by default it will take the current server name, we can the set the server name as well SET @svrName = @@SERVERNAME SET @sql = 'powershell.exe -c "Get-WmiObject -ComputerName ' + QUOTENAME(@svrName, '''') + ' -Class Win32_Volume -Filter ''DriveType = 3'' | select name,Label,BlockSize | foreach{$_.name+''|''+$_.label+''^''+$_.BlockSize/1024+''*''}"'
